    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 314772,
      "reputation" : 12107,
      "user_id" : 630136,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 91,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/7ef26490ce64f932af9ae6e9e554b036?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "G_H",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/630136/g-h"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 26,
    "last_activity_date" : 1299280382,
    "last_edit_date" : 1299280382,
    "creation_date" : 1299279795,
    "answer_id" : 5200228,
    "question_id" : 5200187,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>A BufferedReader constructor takes a <a href=\"http://download.oracle.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/io/Reader.html\">reader</a> as argument, not an InputStream. You should first create a Reader from your stream, like so:</p>\n\n<pre><code>Reader reader = new InputStreamReader(is);\nBufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(reader);\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Preferrably, you also provide a Charset or character encoding name to the StreamReader constructor. Since a stream just provides bytes, converting these to text means the encoding must be known. If you don't specify it, the system default is assumed.</p>\n"
  } ],
